Review whether the upstream node can hand off to the downstream node. Do not generate long guides; the runtime will compile the final Node Execution Guide. Treat edge_handoff_instruction as user-authored natural-language intent, not as a schema field. The instruction may map artifacts, transform content, summarize files, generate new runtime text, or intentionally ignore upstream artifacts. If the downstream skill can execute the instruction with clear assumptions, return trial_ready instead of needs_instruction and put the assumptions in warnings. Use needs_instruction only when no executable interpretation can be derived, the instruction references unavailable artifacts, or the requested handoff contradicts the downstream skill. Keep the response compact; do not copy skill docs or repeat the full request. Return less than 700 JSON characters.

Required JSON keys: status, summary, warnings, required_user_inputs. Optional keys: blocking_reasons, suggested_edge_instruction, handoff_pattern, validation, resolved_handoff. When status is blocked, incompatible, or needs_instruction, suggested_edge_instruction must be a complete user-applicable handoff instruction, not a question or instruction about what to write.
Choose exactly one handoff_pattern from the Handoff Pattern Catalog below. Do not invent pattern IDs.
When status is ready or trial_ready, resolved_handoff should include relay_mappings: an array of objects with source_output, target_input, and resolver when an upstream artifact is used. For generated content such as 'send current date', use source_output='runtime' and resolver='generated'. Use resolver ids declared by the downstream input contract; do not invent business logic outside the contracts.

